Nuances in Docker That Most Beginners Miss

1. Containers are ephemeral, images are immutable
        • A container is just a running instance of an image.
        • You can delete containers freely; the image stays untouched.
        • But you cannot delete an image if any container (running or exited) still references it.
---
2. `docker stop` vs `docker kill`
        • stop sends a graceful SIGTERM → gives the app time to shut down.
        • kill sends SIGKILL → immediate termination.
        • Use stop unless you know the app is stuck.
---
3. `docker run` vs `docker start`
        • docker run → creates a new container from an image.
        • docker start → starts an existing stopped container.
        • Many beginners accidentally create multiple containers by using run repeatedly.
---
4. Volumes vs Bind Mounts
        • Volumes → managed by Docker, best for production.
        • Bind mounts → map host folders, best for local development.
        • Containers should be stateless; volumes store persistent data.
---
5. Networks matter more than you think
        • Default bridge network isolates containers.
        • Custom bridge networks allow automatic DNS-based container discovery.
        • Example: ping mysql works if both containers are on the same custom network.
---
6. `docker exec` vs `docker attach`
        • exec → open a new shell inside the container (safe).
        • attach → attach to the main process (dangerous; can freeze your terminal).
---
7. `docker logs -f` is your best friend
        • Follow logs in real time.
        • Works even for exited containers (to debug why they crashed).
---
8. `docker system prune` is powerful but dangerous
        • Cleans unused containers, images, networks.
        • But can delete things you didn’t intend.
        • Always run with --dry-run first.